{{Infobox royalty | type = Prince | name =Qutalmish | more = | image = | caption = | succession = [[List of Seljuk sultans of Rûm|Ancestor of the Seljuq sultans of Rum]] | reign = ? – | coronation = | predecessor = [[Arslan Yabgu]] | successor = [[Suleiman ibn Qutulmish]] | full name = | house = [[Seljuq dynasty|House of Seljuq]] | spouse= | father = [[Arslan Yabgu]] | mother = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | place of burial = | religion = [[Sunni Islam]] }} '''Qutalmish''' ({{lang-1ca|قُتَلمِش}}, {{lang-fa|قتلمش}}) (alternative spellings: '''Qutulmush''', '''Kutalmish''', {{lang|tr|'''Kutalmış'''}}) was a Turkic prince who was a member of Seljukid house in the 11th century. His son [[Suleiman ibn Qutulmish|Kutalmışoglu Suleiman]], founded the [[Sultanate of Rum]] in what is now Turkey.
==Sultanate of Rûm== Kutalmish was the son of [[Arslan Yabgu]] and a cousin of [[Tughril]] and played a vital role in the conquests of the [[Seljuq Turks]]. In 1046, he was sent with an army by Tughril to force back the Byzantine army at Ganja and was victorious.<ref>Martin Sicker, ''The Islamic World in Ascendancy: From the Arab Conquests to the Siege of Vienna'', (Greenwood Publishing, 2000), 53.</ref>
He supported a rebellion against Tughril and contested the succession to the throne with [[Alp Arslan]]. (''see'' [[Battle of Damghan (1063)]]) According to the historian [[Ali ibn al-Athir]], Kutalmish knew the sciences of the stars.<ref>''Institutionalisation of Science in the Medreses of pre-Ottoman and Ottoman Turkey'', Ekmeleddin Ihsanoglu, '''Turkish Studies in the History and Philosophy of Science''', Ed. Gürol Irzik and Güven Güzeldere, (Springer, 2005), 267.</ref> His son, [[Suleiman ibn Qutulmish|Suleiman]], was recognized as Sultan of [[Sultanate of Rûm|Rûm]] by [[Malik Shah I]] in 1084.<ref>Köprülü, Mehmed Fuad. The Seljuks of Anatolia: their history and culture according to local Muslim sources. Salt Lake City, Utah: Univ. of Utah Press,(1992), 72.</ref>
==Legacy==
[[Kutalmış]] is a very rare masculine [[Turkish name|Turkish given name]], which is used in memory of Kutalmısh.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}
